Claims Claims 1. An apparatus for controlling the flow of gas into a container, the apparatus comprising: - a primary gas conduit configured to feed inert gas from an inert gas source at a pressure greater than atmospheric pressure to a container configured to receive flammable material; a first gas flow regulating means operably connected to the primary gas conduit, and configured to regulate the flow of gas flowing therethrough; - a secondary gas conduit in fluid communication with the primary gas conduit, and disposed upstream of the first gas flow regulating means; gas storage means operably connected to the secondary gas conduit, and configured to store a volume of inert gas; and a first valve operably connected to the primary or secondary gas conduit, and disposed upstream of the gas storage means, characterised in that the apparatus is configured to switch between a standby mode in which the storage means is not in fluid communication with the inert gas source, and an activated mode in which the storage means is in fluid communication with the inert gas source, and wherein the first flow regulating means is configured to prevent the pressure of the inert gas downstream of the first flow regulating means from exceeding the pressure of the inert gas in the storage means. 2. An apparatus according to claim 1, wherein the container is a storage silo. 3. An apparatus according to either claim 1 or claim 2, wherein the flammable material comprises a biomass substance, and is in the form of pellets and/or dust. 4. An apparatus according to any preceding claim, wherein the inert gas source comprises a liquid gas store, a Pressure Swing Adsorption (PSA) unit, a membrane nitrogen generator plant, or any other commercially available means of on-site inert gas generation. 5. An apparatus according to any preceding claim, wherein the inert gas comprises nitrogen gas and/or carbon dioxide and/or argon. 6. An apparatus according to any preceding claim, wherein the apparatus comprises a restriction orifice operably connected to the primary gas conduit, and disposed downstream of the first flow regulating means, wherein the orifice is configured to reduce the pressure of gas flowing therethrough. 7. An apparatus according to any preceding claim, wherein the apparatus comprises control means configured to switch the apparatus between the standby mode and the activated mode. 8. An apparatus according to claim 7, wherein the control means is configured to send a signal to the first valve to switch the apparatus between standby and activated modes. 9. An apparatus according to any preceding claim, wherein the first valve comprises a two-port valve in which first and second ports are operably connected to the secondary gas conduit, and when the apparatus is in standby mode, the first valve is configured so that the storage means is not in fluid communication with the inert gas source such that inert gas cannot flow therethrough, and when the apparatus is activated, the first valve is configured such that the storage means is in fluid communication with the inert gas source such that inert gas can flow therethrough. 10. An apparatus according to any of claims 1 to 8, wherein the first valve comprises a three-port valve, in which first and second ports are operably connected to the secondary gas conduit, and a third port is operably connected to a first vent line, and when the apparatus is in standby mode, the storage means is in fluid communication with the first vent line, and when the apparatus is activated the storage means is not in fluid communication with the first vent line. 11. An apparatus according to any preceding claim, wherein the first gas flow regulating means comprises a backpressure regulator comprising a loading mechanism, a sensing element and a control element. 12. An apparatus according to claim 11, wherein the first flow regulating means comprises a dome loaded regulator, wherein the loading mechanism comprises a dome in fluid communication with the gas storage means. 13. An apparatus according to any preceding claim, wherein the apparatus comprises a second gas flow regulating means in operable communication with the secondary gas conduit, and disposed upstream of the gas storage means, and is configured to restrict the flow of the inert gas into the storage means. 14. An apparatus according to claim 13, wherein the second flow regulating means is disposed downstream of the first valve. 15. An apparatus according to either claim 13 or 14, wherein the second flow regulating means has a flow coefficient (Cv) of less than 0.1, or less than 0.01. 16. An apparatus according to any one of claims 13 to 15, wherein the second flow regulating means comprises a restriction orifice. 17. An apparatus according to any one of claims 13 to 15, wherein second flow regulating means comprises a metering needle valve. 18. An apparatus according to any preceding claim, wherein the apparatus comprises a second vent line operably connected to the secondary gas conduit and/or storage means, and disposed downstream of the first valve, and a vent valve operably connected to the second vent line, wherein when the apparatus is activated, the storage means is not in fluid communication with the second vent line, and when the apparatus is in standby mode, the storage means is in fluid communication with the second vent line. 19. An apparatus according to any preceding claim, wherein the first valve is operably connected to the secondary gas conduit, and disposed upstream of the gas storage means, and the apparatus comprises a second valve operably connected to the primary gas conduit, and disposed upstream of the first flow regulating means, and when the apparatus is in standby mode, the first gas flow regulating means is not in fluid communication with the inert gas source, and when the apparatus is in activated mode, the first gas flow regulating means is in fluid communication with the inert gas source. 20. An apparatus according to claim 19, wherein the second valve comprises an actuated isolation valve system. 21. An apparatus according to claim 19, wherein the further valve comprises a further solenoid valve, and the control means is configured to send a digital signal to the further solenoid valve to switch the apparatus between standby mode and activated mode. 22. An apparatus according to any preceding claim, wherein the apparatus comprises a further flow regulating means operably connected to the secondary gas conduit, and configured to limit the pressure of the inert gas downstream thereof. 23. An apparatus according to claim 22, wherein the further flow regulating means comprises a pilot regulator. 24. An apparatus according to either of claims 22 or 23, wherein the further flow regulating means is disposed upstream of the gas storage means. 25. Use of an apparatus according to any one of claims 1 to 24 to control the flow of gas into a container. 26. Use of an apparatus according to claim 25, to control the flow of inert gas into the container in order to:- (i) inert the atmosphere in a container's headspace to minimise the risk of its contents from self-heating, (ii) inert a container's headspace in the event of a fire occurring at the surface of the container's contents, and/or (iii) provide an inert atmosphere in a container in the event of a high risk of imminent explosion therein. 27. A method of controlling the flow of gas into a container from an inert gas source, the method comprising: splitting a flow of gas from an inert gas source into a primary stream and a secondary stream; feeding the secondary stream into a storage means thereby gradually increasing the pressure therein; 

 feeding the primary stream passed a restriction point at a rate configured to prevent the pressure of the inert gas downstream of the restriction point from exceeding the pressure of the inert gas in the storage means; and releasing the primary stream into the container. 28. A method according to claim 27, wherein the method comprises controlling the rate at which the secondary stream is fed into the storage means. 29. A method according to either of claims 27 or 28, wherein the method comprises an additional step, carried out subsequent to the step of feeding the primary stream passed the restriction point and prior to releasing the primary stream into the headspace, comprising reducing the pressure of the primary stream to approximately atmospheric pressure. 30. A method according to any one of claims 27 to 29, wherein the method comprises an initial step of switching the ports of a first valve, causing the inert gas source to be in fluid communication with the storage means. 31. A method according to claim 30, wherein the step of switching the ports of the first valve comprises sending a digital signal to a first solenoid valve. 32. A method according to either of claims 30 or 31, wherein the initial step also comprises switching the ports of a second valve thereby causing the restriction point to be in fluid communication with the inert gas source. 33. A method according to claim 32, wherein the step of switching the ports of the second valve comprises sending a digital signal to a second solenoid valve. 34. A method according to any one of claims 27 to 33, wherein the method comprises preventing the pressure of the inert gas in the storage means from exceeding a predetermined pressure. 35. A method according to any one of claims 27 to 34, wherein the method comprises allowing a desired volume of inert gas to be released into the container, and preferably a headspace thereof, and once the desired volume of inert gas has been released into the container, the method comprises: 

 stopping the flow of the secondary stream into the storage means; and venting inert gas from the storage means. 36. A method according to claim 35, wherein the step of stopping the flow of the secondary stream into the storage means comprises switching the ports of the first valve causing the inert gas source to not be in fluid communication with the storage means, and preferably also causing the storage means to be in fluid communication with a first vent line. 37. A method according to claim 35, wherein the step of switching the ports of the first valve comprises sending a digital signal to the first solenoid valve. 38. A method according to any one of claims 35 to 37, wherein once the desired volume of inert gas has been released into the headspace the method comprises switching the ports of a second valve causing the restriction point to not be in fluid communication with the inert gas source. 39. A method according to claim 38, wherein the step of switching the ports of the second valve comprises sending a digital signal to the second solenoid valve. 40. A method according to any of claims 35 to 39, wherein the step of venting the inert gas from the storage means comprises switching the ports of a third valve thereby causing the storage means to be in fluid communication with a second vent line. 41. A method according to claim 40, wherein the step of switching the ports of the third valve comprises sending a digital signal to a third solenoid valve.
